Have used for 5+ years now...it has saved me much time and frustration!  Very much worth the purchase of pro. A few tips to users....take a picture with your camera, it is much faster and focuses better than the app camera (my reason for 4 stars). Photograph your item* with a DARK back ground being sure the dark shows along all edges of the item* (*such as a receipt or a document) this will assist the autocrop.  When ready...open the scanner app, select the image (gallery) icon and select the photo you took with your camera and proceed to crop and save file as if you took the photo thru the app. You have to repeat the process for each photo but it is still faster and clearer...imo. I deal with letter and legal size docs all the time...when I proceed as I suggested above...I can photo docs quickly, I check my photos to make sure clear...and I am on my way.  I can work the scanner for a pdf file when I need to, then fax, email, or save however I need.  At a small fraction of the space than a photo...just another plus. I have also gone thru 3 phones and each time was no hassle to reinstall pro...kudos to the tech team and Google play

This is the fourth Android scanner app I've tried.  PROS:  Most thought-out, intuitive document processing UI, with most advanced options (I bought the Pro version) and settings.  CONS:  Like others, I found that using the advanced image adjustments (contrast,  brightness)  in the BW settings at least, allowed me only one adjustment before preview display went completely black. It's a bug I feel confident will be addressed.  SUGGESTIONS: - figure out a way to move access from the settings options to the active scan window -- example: Quality settings - Give a TRUE bw (1 bit) image option. I did a simple test of a scan of black and white text. The final image resolution in the outputted PDF was a decent 267 ppi, BUT... it was not a black and white image embedded in the PDF, it wasn't even a greyscale image. It was a high contrast RGB. Which explained it's 880k file size. I used Acrobat Pro to edit that image in Photoshop to straight 1 bit black and white at the same resolution, and re-saved the image back into the PDF and saved it off as a new copy. The resulting file size was 49k. Note that true black and white PDFs print MUCH much faster than faux black and whites too!
